		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../atem.png" alt="ATEM 2006 SI"></a><br><code>atem2006s/paper06</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Integration of Safety Analysis in Model-Driven Software Development</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MiguelAdeMiguel.html">Miguel A. de Miguel</a>, <a href="../profile/JavierFernándezBriones.html">Javier Fernández Briones</a>, <a href="../profile/JuanPedroSilva.html">Juan Pedro Silva</a>, <a href="../profile/AlejandroAlonso.html">Alejandro Alonso</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/iet-sen:20070050">10.1049/iet-sen:20070050</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/cp:20060228"><em>Integration of safety analysis and software development methods (IET CP 2006)</em></a> &amp; <a href="https://dl.ifip.org/db/conf/seus/seus2007/BrionesMSA07.pdf"><em>Application of Safety Analyses in Model Driven Development (SEUS 2007)</em></a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is about coupling/integrating safety-analysis languages (FTA/FMECA) with software modelling languages (e.g., UML) in an MDD toolchain.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5a.html"><span class="tagL">T5A: Requirements</span></a><ul><li> Safety objectives and safety requirements are first-class modelling concepts and the approach aims to verify architectures against them.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The integration relies on language mappings/model transformations between architecture models and safety-analysis models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It introduces/uses metamodels, profiles and a platform-independent safety language as meta-language artefacts to bridge domains.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
</html>
